      <abstract>
        <p>Clark County Museum in Las Vegas opens exhibit on prewar motor courts which includes relocated motor court cabin (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Before Las Vegas hotels began belching flame and impersonating Venice and Paris, there were motor courts, tiny roadside collections of cabins where tired motorists would pull in at the end of a long drive. They often had no air-conditioning, and the closest thing to a data port was a newspaper box.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Before Las Vegas hotels began belching flame and impersonating Venice and Paris, there were motor courts, tiny roadside collections of cabins where tired motorists would pull in at the end of a long drive. They often had no air-conditioning, and the closest thing to a data port was a newspaper box.</p>
        <p>Now the Clark County Museum in Las Vegas is honoring that era with a new exhibit: a prewar motor court cabin that was moved from downtown Las Vegas. Visitors can walk inside the cabin, which is furnished in the style of the era. The Clark County Museum is at 1830 South Boulder Highway, (702) 455-7955; general admission is $1.50.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH SIANO</p>
        <p>TRAVEL ADVISORY: MUSEUM</p>
      </block>
